Getting started:
    Non-spacing mode might be useful, but don't stick with it too much
    Dunno what order is best for memorizing, need everything in the end
    settings for monkey/typey: ?
    lock in that home position!
    In the end, need to memorize syllables. It's all muscle memory and there's a lot to memorize

Annoying things:
    RN- and -NR are flipped. Gets a bit confusing.
    Vowels suck, no way around it
    Some things simply don't generate and need to span both hands, i.e. middle -> DLE- doesn't work (also TLE-)

Overall rules:
    Steno order - strokes generate based on the layout
        Mostly. There are exceptions - see the chart. Especially -HT and -GHT
    A left consonant will add a space, unless suppressed with an asterisk
    A left WHNR will space the next word (due to the previous rule - used for opening consonants)
    If you need more consonants in the middle, you'll need to break up the chord

Chord-generating rules:
    Not a rule, but most everything just works for English
    -RN switches to alternate outputs
        -NG = NG, -RNG = GN
        (and the LD thing)
        - I don't think there's a left hand version
    -Be aware of the second S - it gets used a lot (-F in steno)
    -If there's a chord you want the map has plenty of empty spaces
        rules.rb for syllables that get combined, jackdaw.py for entire chords (can't be combined)
    -left quote, right quote and apostrophe are different (due to word binding)


